T1  - Monetary mystique: Secrecy and central banking
AU  - Goodfriend, Marvin
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 17
IS  - 1
SP  - 63
EP  - 92
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(86)90006-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393286900061
AB  - The paper contains a discussion of the role of secrecy in the implementation of monetary policy. It documents the Federal Reserve's defense of secrecy as argued in a recent Freedom of Information Act suit. The Federal Reserve's arguments are evaluated on the basis of economic theory. Theoretical papers related to the secrecy issue are reviewed. The discussion highlights a number of potential benefits and costs of central bank secrecy, and identifies some conditions under which secrecy could be socially beneficial.
ER  - 
